    <main class="container" role="main" aria-labelledby="page-title">
        <h1 id="page-title">USA‑Nigeria Standoff: Military Threat, Religious Claims, and Sovereignty at Stake</h1>

        <h2>Lead</h2>
        <p>In early November 2025, Donald Trump ignited international alarm by threatening possible U.S. military intervention in Nigeria over what he described as “very large numbers” of Christians being killed in the country. Nigeria rejected the threat as a breach of its sovereignty, while international analysts warned that the situation is far more complex than the U.S. framing suggests.</p>

        <h2>Key Facts & Timeline</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><time datetime="2025-11-01">1 Nov 2025</time>: Trump instructed the Pentagon to prepare for potential military action in Nigeria, including troops or air strikes if Nigeria fails to act on widespread Christian killings. <span class="source">[Reuters]</span></li>
            <li><time datetime="2025-11-02">2–3 Nov 2025</time>: Nigeria welcomed counter-terrorism assistance only if its sovereignty is respected. <span class="source">[Reuters]</span></li>
            <li>Nigerian spokesperson emphasised that many deaths are Muslims, not Christians. <span class="source">[Reuters]</span></li>
            <li><time datetime="2025-11-05">5 Nov 2025</time>: Nigeria launched a $2.25B Eurobond sale, showing markets were largely stable. <span class="source">[Reuters]</span></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Context: What’s Really Going On?</h2>
        <h3>Security & Violence Landscape</h3>
        <p>Nigeria faces multifaceted insecurity: Boko Haram, ISWAP insurgencies, banditry, kidnappings, and herder-farmer conflicts in the Middle Belt. Many conflicts are not purely about religion. <span class="source">[TheCable]</span></p>

        <p>Of 23,931 conflict events from 2020–24, ~4.3% targeted religious groups. Ethnic/communal events caused far more fatalities (4,990 vs 779). <span class="source">[TheCable]</span></p>

        <h3>The U.S. Angle: Why Intervene?</h3>
        <p>Trump and some U.S. legislators cite alleged Christian massacres. Nigeria is designated a “Country of Particular Concern” for religious freedom. Experts suggest strategic interests and political signaling may also be factors. <span class="source">[Politico]</span></p>

        <h3>Nigeria’s Stance & Sovereignty</h3>
        <p>Nigeria insists outside military operations must be partnerships, not imposed. Violence affects both Muslims and Christians. External intervention without consent would set a dangerous precedent. <span class="source">[Reuters]</span></p>

        <h2>What’s at Stake?</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>For Nigeria:</strong> Sovereignty risks, escalation, anti-foreign sentiment, complex internal security strategy.</li>
            <li><strong>For Christians & Muslim women:</strong> Inclusive storytelling matters. Both communities are affected.</li>
            <li><strong>For the U.S.:</strong> Military engagement without clear legal framework risks backlash and destabilizing partnerships.</li>
            <li><strong>For your audience:</strong> Global events impact productivity, faith, and women’s leadership.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Possible Scenarios & What to Watch</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Possible scenarios">
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Scenario</th>
                    <th>Likely Outcomes</th>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Diplomatic resolution – Nigeria & U.S. negotiate enhanced cooperation without boots on the ground</td>
                    <td>Violence continues domestically, Nigeria retains sovereignty; less U.S. domestic political gain.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Limited U.S. action – Air strikes or special forces cooperation</td>
                    <td>Risk of civilian casualties, instability; displacement of local women.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Full U.S. intervention without Nigeria’s consent – ground troops + broad mission</td>
                    <td>Major diplomatic crisis, regional spill-over; high internal risk.</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

